# 1. PROJECT CONTEXT
# ============================================================

## Project Overview
"Let's Cook" is a full-stack recipe suggestion web app that helps home cooks
discover meals they can make right now based on their available ingredients.
Users manage a pantry inventory, receive smart recipe suggestions with
ingredient match percentages, view full recipe details, and track their
cooking history.

## Tech Stack
- Framework:     Next.js 14 (App Router)
- Styling:       TailwindCSS (custom orange/green theme)
- Language:      TypeScript (strict mode)
- Database:      PostgreSQL (via Prisma ORM)
- Auth:          NextAuth.js (JWT strategy)
- API:           Next.js API Routes (/app/api/*)
- Testing:       Jest + React Testing Library (unit/integration), Playwright (E2E)
- CI/CD:         GitHub Actions
- Deployment:    Vercel (production)
- Node version:  18+

## Folder Structure
```
/app
  /api              → Next.js API route handlers
    /auth           → NextAuth config
    /recipes        → Recipe endpoints
    /ingredients    → Ingredient endpoints
    /pantry         → User pantry endpoints
    /cooking-log    → Cooking history endpoints
  /(routes)         → Page components
    /page.tsx       → Homepage (recipe catalog)
    /pantry/        → Pantry management page
    /recipes/[id]/  → Recipe detail page
    /history/       → Cooking history page
/components
  /ui               → Reusable UI primitives (Button, Card, Modal, Toast)
  /layout           → Header, Navigation, FilterPanel
  /recipes          → RecipeCard, RecipeGrid, RecipeDetail
  /pantry           → IngredientList, IngredientSearch, GroceryList
/lib
  /db.ts            → Prisma client singleton
  /auth.ts          → NextAuth config export
  /utils.ts         → Shared utility functions
  /types.ts         → Shared TypeScript types and interfaces
/prisma
  schema.prisma     → Database schema
  /migrations       → Prisma migration files
  seed.ts           → Database seed script (23 recipes, 85+ ingredients)
/tests
  /unit             → Jest unit tests
  /integration      → Jest integration tests (API routes)
  /e2e              → Playwright end-to-end tests
```

## Naming Conventions
- Components:       PascalCase (e.g., RecipeCard.tsx)
- Hooks:            camelCase prefixed with "use" (e.g., usePantry.ts)
- API routes:       kebab-case folders (e.g., /api/cooking-log)
- Database tables:  snake_case (e.g., recipe_ingredients)
- CSS classes:      Tailwind utility classes only — no custom CSS files
- Variables:        camelCase
- Constants:        UPPER_SNAKE_CASE
- Types/Interfaces: PascalCase, prefix interfaces with "I" only if ambiguous

## Coding Standards
- TypeScript strict mode — no implicit `any`
- All async functions must have proper error handling (try/catch)
- API responses must follow this shape:
  { data: T | null, error: string | null, status: number }
- No inline styles — use Tailwind classes exclusively
- Components should be small and single-responsibility
- Avoid prop drilling deeper than 2 levels — use context or hooks
- All user-facing strings should be in English

## Testing Strategy
- Target: 80%+ coverage across unit + integration tests
- Unit tests: all utility functions, hooks, and pure components
- Integration tests: all API route handlers using supertest
- E2E tests: critical user flows (login, pantry update, recipe suggestion)
- Test files live alongside source: ComponentName.test.tsx
- Use React Testing Library queries (getByRole, getByText) — avoid getByTestId

