# 3. SCRUM & WORKFLOW INSTRUCTIONS
# ============================================================

## Branch Naming
Format: <type>/<issue-number>-<short-description>
Examples:
  feature/4-pantry-ingredient-search
  feature/5-recipe-suggestions
  fix/12-grocery-list-bulk-add
  chore/1-nextjs-project-setup
  docs/9-api-documentation

## Commit Message Format
Format: <type>(#<issue>): <short description>
Examples:
  feat(#4): add ingredient search with dropdown
  fix(#12): correct bulk add state management
  chore(#1): initialize Next.js with Tailwind
  test(#5): add unit tests for match percentage util
  docs(#9): add OpenAPI spec for recipes endpoint

Types: feat | fix | chore | test | docs | refactor | style

## PR Workflow
- Every PR must reference its GitHub Issue: "Closes #<issue-number>"
- PR title must match commit format
- PRs require passing CI (tests + lint) before merge
- Keep PRs small and focused — one issue per PR
- Add screenshots for any UI changes

## Referencing Issues in Code
- Use TODO comments with issue numbers for known gaps:
  // TODO(#14): add real-time update when pantry changes
- Never leave untracked TODOs — always link to a GitHub Issue

# ============================================================
# 4. DO'S AND DON'TS
# ============================================================

## DO
- Use Prisma for all database queries — never raw SQL
- Use NextAuth.js session for auth checks in API routes
- Use TailwindCSS utility classes for all styling
- Use TypeScript interfaces from /lib/types.ts for shared types
- Return consistent API response shapes: { data, error, status }
- Write tests alongside every new component or API route
- Use Zod for runtime validation on all API request bodies
- Use next/image for all recipe images (optimized loading)
- Handle loading and error states in every component
- Use React Server Components where data fetching is needed (no useEffect for fetches)

## DON'T
- Don't use localStorage for user data — all persistence must go through the database
- Don't use inline styles or custom CSS files — Tailwind only
- Don't use `any` type in TypeScript
- Don't skip error handling in async functions
- Don't create new color classes — use amber-500 and green-500 from the design system
- Don't use class components — functional components with hooks only
- Don't make direct database calls from client components
- Don't commit secrets or .env files
- Don't use `console.log` in production code — use a proper logger or remove before merge
- Don't create API routes without input validation (use Zod)

## Preferred Libraries
- Zod:            Request/response validation
- Prisma:         Database ORM
- NextAuth.js:    Authentication
- Lucide React:   Icons (consistent with existing design)
- next/image:     Image optimization
- Jest + RTL:     Unit and integration testing
- Playwright:     E2E testing

## Security Requirements
- All user-specific API routes must verify NextAuth session
- Passwords handled entirely by NextAuth — never store raw passwords
- Environment variables for all secrets (DATABASE_URL, NEXTAUTH_SECRET, etc.)
- Validate and sanitize all user inputs with Zod before database operations
- Use parameterized queries via Prisma — no raw string interpolation in queries

## Accessibility Requirements
- All interactive elements must have accessible labels (aria-label or visible text)
- Color is never the only indicator of state — always pair with icon or text
- Keyboard navigation must work for all modals and dropdowns
- Images must have descriptive alt text
- Minimum touch target size: 44x44px on mobile

